english:
  title: Preface to the Record of Official Missions by the Grand Councilor
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Poetry, they say, is the expression of one's innermost thoughts. Though the craft of words may vary—some refined, some crude—the inclinations of the heart cannot help but reveal themselves in subtle ways. Thus poetry allows us to observe a person's virtue and examine the conduct of their life.

    Our Grand Councilor, Lord of Deok-seong, comes from a lineage of accumulated goodness. Through generations his house has flourished; connected to the imperial family, he stands as protector of the royal house. His renown and prosperity spread like fragrance, earning him the respect of his age. One would think such a man would have no time for idle verse and song. Yet his nature is genuine and refined, his spirit open and expansive. He delights in quiet conversation with old friends about the journey of life, spending his days in the pleasures of poetry and wine, his manner so engaging that those around him forget their weariness.

    In the year of the Rooster under the Zhizheng era, he received imperial summons and journeyed to court. There, favored by the imperial gaze, he was showered with honors and gifts. The Emperor himself bestowed upon him fragrant incense, saying: "That distant Eastern realm—I have walked its paths and seen therein its sacred mountains and benevolent shrines. I grant you this precious incense. Let it carry my will to your people, not for my own sake, but that the common folk may receive blessing."

    Returning eastward with this charge, he devoted himself to his mission. In his moments of leisure, whenever inspiration stirred, he would compose verses to ease his spirit. A certain Korean gentleman who traveled with him collected these poems and brought them to me. Reading through them again and again, I could not help but marvel. "How beautiful these verses!" I said. "It is the nature of those touched by favor and fortune to grow proud and corrupt; righteousness fades daily as baseness gains strength. Few can turn back and reflect. Yet in this collection, not one line boasts or aggrandizes. The vulgar dust of the world has been swept away. And in his words of returning to till the fields and grow melons, there resides a profound caution against excess—a warning against satiety.

    "Those scholars who cannot stand near the great and seek to understand their virtue and character should study this record."

    The Korean gentleman said, "I shall have it copied. Will you write a preface?" I declined, but he insisted: "Such is the command of Lord Deok-seong. This is no private matter." Unable to refuse further, I ventured: "If one were to discuss the meaning of these poems, it would be like a bird dizzied by the sound of instruments. To write a preface at the beginning would be like a fox borrowing the tiger's might. So I have dipped my brush many times, only to lay it down again. Yet this is as it should be—when winnowing grain, the chaff naturally rises to the fore."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'fragrant incense' (天香) mentioned here is a symbolic gift representing imperial favor and a mandate to spread the Emperor's benevolence to the people of Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'returning to till the fields and grow melons' evokes the classical ideal of the virtuous official who retires from power to live simply, symbolizing humility and freedom from ambition.
  - key: ''
    value: The final metaphor about winnowing grain—with chaff rising naturally to the front—is Lee Dal-choong's modest way of acknowledging that his preface, though imperfect, serves its natural purpose.
